<p><b>Hadith</b> (<b><span lang="ar" xml:lang="ar">الحديث</span></b> <a href="/wiki/Romanization_of_Arabic" title="Romanization of Arabic">transliteration</a>: <span lang="ar-Latn" title="Arabic transliteration" class="Unicode" style="white-space:normal; text-decoration: none" xml:lang="ar-Latn">al-ḥadī<u>th</u></span>, pl. <i>aḥadī<u>th</u></i>; <i>lit</i>. "narrative") are oral <a href="/wiki/Tradition" title="Tradition">traditions</a> relating to the words and deeds of the <a href="/wiki/Prophets_of_Islam" title="Prophets of Islam">Islamic prophet</a> <a href="/wiki/Muhammad" title="Muhammad">Muhammad</a>. Hadith collections are regarded by all traditional <a href="/wiki/Madhab" title="Madhab" class="mw-redirect">schools of jurisprudence</a> as important tools for determining the <a href="/wiki/Muslim" title="Muslim">Muslim</a> way of life, the <i><a href="/wiki/Sunnah" title="Sunnah">sunnah</a></i>.</p>
